<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a healthy age gap in a relationship?", answer: "Researchers have studied age gaps in marriages for decades. The most widely cited finding (Drefahl 2010) is that couples within 1–3 years of each other have the lowest divorce rate. Gaps of 5 years are 18% more likely to divorce, gaps of 10 years are 39% more likely, and gaps of 20+ years are 95% more likely. That said, plenty of large-gap relationships work — the statistics don't predict any individual couple's outcome." },
  { question: "What is the half-your-age-plus-seven rule?", answer: "It's a social rule of thumb that the youngest socially acceptable partner age is your age divided by 2, plus 7. So a 30-year-old's lower bound is 22, a 40-year-old's is 27, and a 50-year-old's is 32. The maximum is the inverse: (your age − 7) × 2. The rule appeared in print as early as 1901 (in 'Her Royal Highness Woman' by Maxime Du Camp) and has stuck around because it roughly tracks what most cultures consider acceptable across the lifespan." },
  { question: "Does the half-plus-seven rule apply to teens?", answer: "Not really. The rule breaks down for teenagers and young adults — a 14-year-old's lower bound is 14, which technically allows same-age dating, but a 16-year-old's lower bound is 15. Many countries have legal age-of-consent laws that override social rules, and the calculator does not account for those. For anyone under 18, defer to local age-of-consent laws and parental judgment, not a math rule." },
  { question: "How does the calculator handle leap years?", answer: "The calculator counts whole calendar years, then counts the remaining months and days exactly using each month's actual length. Leap days (Feb 29) are handled correctly because the calculator works in calendar dates, not in a fixed 365-day year. If you were born on Feb 29, your 'official' birthday in non-leap years is March 1." },
  { question: "Is age gap a deal breaker for marriage?", answer: "No single factor determines marriage success, but research consistently finds that smaller age gaps correlate with higher reported satisfaction and lower divorce rates. The factors that matter more: shared values, similar life stages, communication style, and conflict resolution. A 10-year gap between two people in the same life stage (both established in careers, both wanting kids on the same timeline) often works better than a 2-year gap between people in different life stages." }
]) %>

