    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How the Age Gap Calculator Works</h2>
      <p>
        Enter the two birth dates and the calculator finds the exact difference in years, months, and days using calendar arithmetic. It also computes the current age of each person and runs the classic half-your-age-plus-seven check, which says the minimum socially acceptable partner age for an older person is their age divided by 2, plus 7. The default example shows a roughly 3-year gap, which falls well within the safest range according to relationship research.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>What Research Says About Age Gaps</h2>
      <p>
        Stockholm University demographer Sven Drefahl analyzed Danish marriage records and found that couples within 1–3 years of age had the lowest divorce rates. Each additional year of gap added a few percentage points to the divorce risk. By 10 years apart, the divorce rate climbed about 39% above the baseline; at 20 years apart, it was nearly double. The pattern holds across countries — Atlanta-based Emory University found similar results in US census data. None of this predicts any individual couple's outcome, but the trend is consistent enough that life stage compatibility matters more than people often think.
      </p>

      <h2>The Half-Your-Age-Plus-Seven Rule</h2>
      <p>
        The rule has been around since at least 1901 and has stuck around because it tracks intuitive social comfort across the lifespan. The lower bound for a 30-year-old is 22; for a 40-year-old, it's 27; for a 50-year-old, it's 32. The corresponding upper bound is double minus seven: a 30-year-old's max is 46, a 40-year-old's is 66. The rule isn't a law and isn't a moral judgment — it's a quick gut-check that helps people notice when a gap is large enough to warrant thinking about life stages.
      </p>

      <h2>When Larger Gaps Work Best</h2>
      <p>
        Large age gaps tend to succeed when both partners are in the same life stage despite the calendar — both established in careers, both wanting kids on the same timeline, both with compatible health and energy. They struggle most when life stages diverge: a 28-year-old who wants to start a family with a 55-year-old who has adult children faces a structural mismatch that no amount of love can fix. If you're considering a relationship with a meaningful gap, talk explicitly about the next 10–20 years before getting serious.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Is a 5-year age gap a lot?</h3>
      <p>No — 5 years is well within typical relationship norms and divorce statistics show only a small uptick.</p>

      <h3>What's the average age gap in marriages?</h3>
      <p>In the US the average is about 2.3 years, with the husband older. About 8% of couples have gaps of 10 years or more.</p>

      <h3>Does the half-plus-seven rule apply to women dating older men?</h3>
      <p>Yes — the rule is symmetric. It applies to either partner being older, regardless of gender.</p>

      <h3>How accurate is the day count?</h3>
      <p>Exact, including leap years. The calculator works in calendar dates, not fixed 365-day years.</p>

      <h3>Why does my calculation show one less day than I expected?</h3>
      <p>The calculator counts complete days between dates. If you want birthday-inclusive counting, add 1.</p>

      <%= render "shared/print_button" %>
